# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Scott received his B.A. in Mathematics from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1954.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] He wrote his Ph.D. thesis on *Convergent Sequences of Complete Theories* under the supervision of Alonzo Church while at Princeton, and defended his thesis in 1958.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] After completing his Ph.D. studies, he moved to the University of Chicago, working as an instructor there until 1960.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] In 1959, he published a joint paper with Michael O.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Rabin, a colleague from Princeton, titled *Finite Automata and Their Decision Problem* (Scott and Rabin 1959) which introduced the idea of nondeterministic machines to automata theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] This work led to the joint bestowal of the Turing Award on the two, for the introduction of this fundamental concept of computational complexity theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Scott took up a post as assistant professor of mathematics, back at the University of California, Berkeley, and involved himself with classical issues in mathematical logic, especially set theory and Tarskian model theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] He proved that the axiom of constructibility is incompatible with the existence of a measurable cardinal, a result considered *seminal* in the evolution of set theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] During this period he started supervising Ph.D. students, such as James Halpern (*Contributions to the Study of the Independence of the Axiom of Choice*) and Edgar Lopez-Escobar (*Infinitely Long Formulas with Countable Quantifier Degrees*).
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Scott also began working on modal logic in this period, beginning a collaboration with John Lemmon, who moved to Claremont, California, in 1963.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Scott was especially interested in Arthur Prior's approach to tense logic and the connection to the treatment of time in natural-language semantics, and began collaborating with Richard Montague (Copeland 2004), whom he had known from his days as an undergraduate at Berkeley.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Later, Scott and Montague independently discovered an important generalisation of Kripke semantics for modal and tense logic, called Scott-Montague semantics (Scott 1970).
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] John Lemmon and Scott began work on a modal-logic textbook that was interrupted by Lemmon's death in 1966.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Scott eventually published the work as *An Introduction to Modal Logic* (Lemmon & Scott, 1977).
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Following an initial observation of Robert Solovay, Scott formulated the concept of Boolean-valued model, as Solovay and Petr Vopěnka did likewise at around the same time.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] In 1967, Scott published a paper, *A Proof of the Independence of the Continuum Hypothesis*, in which he used Boolean-valued models to provide an alternate analysis of the independence of the continuum hypothesis to that provided by Paul Cohen.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] This work led to the award of the Leroy P.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Scott took up a post as Professor of Mathematical Logic on the Philosophy faculty of the University of Oxford in 1972.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] He was member of Merton College while at Oxford and is now an Honorary Fellow of the college.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] This period saw Scott working with Christopher Strachey, and the two managed, despite administrative pressures, to do work on providing a mathematical foundation for the semantics of programming languages, the work for which Scott is best known.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Together, their work constitutes the Scott–Strachey approach to denotational semantics, an important and seminal contribution to theoretical computer science.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] One of Scott's contributions is his formulation of domain theory, allowing programs involving recursive functions and looping-control constructs to be given denotational semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] Additionally, he provided a foundation for the understanding of infinitary and continuous information through domain theory and his theory of information systems.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] At Carnegie Mellon University, Scott proposed the theory of equilogical spaces as a successor theory to domain theory; among its many advantages, the category of equilogical spaces is a cartesian closed category, whereas the category of domains is not.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] In 1994, he was inducted as a Fellow of the Association for Computing Machinery.
[src:denotational-semantics/dana-scott] In 2012 he became a fellow of the American Mathematical Society.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The **denotational semantics of the Actor model** is the subject of denotational domain theory for Actors.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The historical development of this subject is recounted in [Hewitt 2008b].
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The denotational theory of computational system semantics is concerned with finding mathematical objects that represent what systems do.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Collections of such objects are called domains.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The Actor uses the domain of event diagram scenarios.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] It is usual to assume some properties of the domain, such as the existence of limits of chains (see cpo) and a bottom element.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Various additional properties are often reasonable and helpful: the article on domain theory has more details.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] A domain is typically a partial order, which can be understood as an order of definedness.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] For instance, given event diagram scenarios x and y, one might let "x≤y" mean that "y extends the computations x".
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] It would be expected that **progression**S would be *monotone*, *i.e.*, if x≤y then **progression**S(x)≤**progression**S(y).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] This last stated property of **progression**S is called ω-continuity.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] A central question of denotational semantics is to characterize when it is possible to create denotations (meanings) according to the equation for **Denote**S.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] A fundamental theorem of computational domain theory is that if **progression**S is ω-continuous then **Denote**S will exist.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The above equation motivates the terminology that **Denote**S is a *fixed point* of **progression**S.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Furthermore, this fixed point is least among all fixed points of **progression**S.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] An important aspect of denotational semantics of programming languages is compositionality, by which the denotation of a program is constructed from denotations of its parts.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] For example, consider the expression "<expression1> + <expression2>".
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Compositionality in this case is to provide a meaning for "<expression1> + <expression2>" in terms of the meanings of <expression1> and <expression2>.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The Actor model provides a modern and very general way the compositionality of programs can be analyzed.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Scott and Strachey [1971] proposed that the semantics of programming languages be reduced to the semantics of the lambda calculus and thus inherit the denotational semantics of the lambda calculus.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] However, it turned out that concurrent computation could not be implemented in the lambda calculus (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Thus there arose the problem of how to provide modular denotational semantics for concurrent programming languages.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] One solution to this problem is to use the Actor model of computation.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In Actor model, programs are Actors that are sent Eval messages with the address of an environment (explained below) so that programs inherit their denotational semantics from the denotational semantics of the Actor model (an idea published in Hewitt [2006]).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Environments hold the bindings of identifiers.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] When an environment is sent a Lookup message with the address of an identifier **x**, it returns the latest (lexical) binding of **x**.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] As an example of how this works consider the lambda expression <L> below which implements a tree data structure when supplied with parameters for a leftSubTree and rightSubTree.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] When such a tree is given a parameter message "getLeft", it return leftSubTree and likewise when given the message "getRight" it returns rightSubTree.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Consider what happens when an expression of the form "(<L> 1 2)" is sent an Eval message with environment **E**.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] One semantics for application expressions such as this one is the following: <L>, 1 and 2 are each sent Eval messages with environment **E**.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The integers 1 and 2 immediately reply to the Eval message with themselves.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] However, <L> responds to the Eval message by creating a closure Actor (process) **C** that has an address (called *body*) for <L> and an address (called *environment*) for **E**.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] For another example consider the Actor for the expression "<expression1> + <expression2>" which has addresses for two other actors (processes) <expression1> and <expression2>.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] When the composite expression Actor (process) receives an Eval message with addresses for an environment Actor **E** and a customer **C**, it sends Eval messages to <expression1> and <expression2> with environment **E** and sends **C** a new Actor (process) **C0**.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In this way, the denotational semantics for process calculi and the Actor model provide a denotational semantics for "<expression1> + <expression2>" in terms of the semantics for <expression1> and <expression2>.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The denotational compositional semantics presented above is very general and can be used for functional, imperative, concurrent, logic, *etc.* programs (see [Hewitt 2008a]).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] For example, it easily provides denotation semantics for constructs that are difficult to formalize using other approaches such as delays and futures.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In his doctoral dissertation, Will Clinger developed the first denotation semantics for the Actor model.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The augmented diagrams are partial computation histories representing "snapshots" [relative to some frame of reference] of a computation on its way to being completed.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] represent computations that have terminated and nonterminating computations that have become infinite.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Concretely, the completed elements are those having non pending events.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] in which some pending event remains pending forever while the number of realized events grows without bound, contrary to the requirement of finite [arrival] delay.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Such a sequence cannot have a limit, because any limit would represent a completed nonterminating computation in which an event is still pending.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] is incomplete because of the requirement of finite arrival delay, which allows any finite delay between an event and an event it activates but rules out infinite delay.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] From the article on Power domains: *P*[D] is the collection of downward-closed subsets of domain D that are also closed under existing least upper bounds of directed sets in D.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Note that while the ordering on *P*[D] is given by the subset relation, least upper bounds do not in general coincide with unions.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] represents a list of possible initial histories of a computation.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] be downward-closed has a clear basis in intuition.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The first reason is that most power domains are simply generalizations of domains that have been used as semantic domains for conventional sequential programs, and such domains are all complete because of the need to compute fixed points in the sequential case.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] which defines a domain of resumptions [Gordon Plotkin 1976].
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] can be defined for any domain whatsoever.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Furthermore the power domain of a domain is essentially the power domain of its ω-completion, so recursive equations involving the power domain of an incomplete domain can still be solved, provide the domains to which the usual constructors (+, ×, →, and *) are applied are ω-complete.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] It happens that defining Actor semantics as in Clinger [1981] does not require solving any recursive equations involving the power domain.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In short, there is no technical impediment to building power domains from incomplete domains.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] , the meaning of program is a specification of the computations that may be performed by the program.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The computations are represented formally by Actor event diagrams.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Greif specified the event diagrams by means of causal axioms governing the behaviors of individual Actors [Greif 1975].
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Henry Baker has presented a nondeterministic interpreter generating instantaneous schedules which then map onto event diagrams.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] He suggested that a corresponding deterministic interpreter operating on sets of instantaneous schedules could be defined using power domain semantics [Baker 1978].
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The semantics presented in [Clinger 1981] is a version of behavioral semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] A program denotes a set of Actor event diagrams.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The set is defined extensionally using power domain semantics rather than intensionally using causal axioms.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The behaviors of individual Actors is defined functionally.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] It is shown, however, that the resulting set of Actor event diagrams consists of exactly those diagrams that satisfy causal axioms expressing the functional behaviors of Actors.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Thus Greif's behavioral semantics is compatible with a denotational power domain semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] , which represent messages on the way to their targets.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Augmenting Actor event diagrams with sets of pending events helps to express the finite delay property, which is characteristic of true concurrency [Schwartz 1979].
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Instead of beginning with a semantics for sequential programs and then trying to extend it for concurrency, Actor semantics views concurrency as primary and obtains the semantics of sequential programs as a special case.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The fact that there exist increasing sequences without least upper bounds may seem strange to those accustomed to thinking about the semantics of sequential programs.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] It may help to point out that the increasing sequences produced by sequential programs all have least upper bounds.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] From the Actor point of view, sequential computations are a special case of concurrent computations, distinguishable by their event diagrams.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The event diagram of a sequential computation has an initial event, and no event activates more than one event.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In other words, the activation ordering of a sequential computation is linear; the event diagram is essentially a conventional execution sequence.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] corresponding to the finite initial segments of a sequential execution sequence all have exactly one pending event, excepting the largest, completed element if the computation terminates.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] has at most one pending event, every pending event in the sequence becomes realized.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Thus Actor semantics includes sequential programs as a special case, and agrees with conventional semantics of such programs.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Hewitt [2006b] published a new denotational semantics for Actors based on Timed Diagrams.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The Timed Diagrams model stands in contrast to Clinger [1981] which constructed an ω-complete power domain from an underlying incomplete diagrammatic domain, which did not include time.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The advantage of the domain Timed Diagrams model is that it is physically motivated and the resulting computations have the desired property of ω-completeness (therefore unbounded nondeterminism) which provides guarantee of service.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Timed Diagrams denotational semantics constructs an ω-complete computational domain for Actor computations.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The delivery time is more than a fixed δ greater than the time of its activating event.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] It will later turn out that the value of δ doesn't matter.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In fact the value of δ can even be allowed to decrease linearly with time to accommodate Moore's Law.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The Actor event timed diagrams form a partially ordered set <**TimedDiagrams**, ≤>.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The diagrams are partial computation histories representing "snapshots" (relative to some frame of reference) of a computation on its way to being completed.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] For d1, d2ε**TimedDiagrams**, d1≤d2 means d1 is a stage the computation could go through on its way to d2 The completed elements of **TimedDiagrams** represent computations that have terminated and nonterminating computations that have become infinite.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The completed elements may be characterized abstractly as the maximal elements of **TimedDiagrams**.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Concretely, the completed elements are those having no pending events.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The finite elements of **TimedDiagrams** are countable where an element xε**TimedDiagrams** is finite (isolated) if and only if D⊆**TimedDiagrams** is directed and x≤VD, there exists dεD with x≤d.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] In other words, x is finite if one must go through x in order to get up to or above x via the limit process.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Every element of **TimedDiagrams** is the least upper bound of a countable increasing sequence of finite elements.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] An Actor computation can progress in many ways.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] 3. subject to the constraint that each event in X is scheduled at least δ after e and every event in X is scheduled at least once in every δ interval after that.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] where ⊥S is the initial configuration of S.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The denotation DenoteS of an Actor system S is the set of all computations of S.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Define the *time abstraction* of a timed diagram to be the diagram with the time annotations removed.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] Using the domain **TimedDiagrams**, which is ω-complete, is important because it provides for the direct expression of the above representation theorem for the denotations of Actor systems by directly constructing a minimal fixed point.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics-of-the-actor-model] The criterion of continuity for the graphs of functions that Scott used to initially develop the denotational semantics of functions can be derived as a consequence of the Actor laws for computation as shown in the next section.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Other approaches providing formal semantics of programming languages include axiomatic semantics and operational semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Broadly speaking, denotational semantics is concerned with finding mathematical objects called domains that represent what programs do.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, programs (or program phrases) might be represented by partial functions or by games between the environment and the system.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] An important tenet of denotational semantics is that *semantics should be compositional*: the denotation of a program phrase should be built out of the denotations of its subphrases.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Denotational semantics originated in the work of Christopher Strachey and Dana Scott published in the early 1970s.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] As originally developed by Strachey and Scott, denotational semantics provided the meaning of a computer program as a function that mapped input into output.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] To give meanings to recursively defined programs, Scott proposed working with continuous functions between domains, specifically complete partial orders.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] As described below, work has continued in investigating appropriate denotational semantics for aspects of programming languages such as sequentiality, concurrency, non-determinism and local state.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Denotational semantics has been developed for modern programming languages that use capabilities like concurrency and exceptions, e.g., Concurrent ML, CSP, and Haskell.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The semantics of these languages is compositional in that the meaning of a phrase depends on the meanings of its subphrases.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, the meaning of the applicative expression `f(E1,E2)` is defined in terms of semantics of its subphrases f, E1 and E2.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] In a modern programming language, E1 and E2 can be evaluated concurrently and the execution of one of them might affect the other by interacting through shared objects causing their meanings to be defined in terms of each other.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Also, E1 or E2 might throw an exception which could terminate the execution of the other one.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The sections below describe special cases of the semantics of these modern programming languages.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Denotational semantics is ascribed to a program phrase as a function from an environment (holding current values of its free variables) to its denotation.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, the phrase `n*m` produces a denotation when provided with an environment that has binding for its two free variables: `n` and `m`.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] If in the environment `n` has the value 3 and `m` has the value 5, then the denotation is 15.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] A function can be represented as a set of ordered pairs of argument and corresponding result values.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, the set {(0,1), (4,3)} denotes a function with result 1 for argument 0, result 3 for the argument 4, and undefined otherwise.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] To provide a meaning for this recursive definition, the denotation is built up as the limit of approximations, where each approximation limits the number of calls to factorial.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] At the beginning, we start with no calls - hence nothing is defined.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] In the next approximation, we can add the ordered pair (0,1), because this doesn't require calling factorial again.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Similarly we can add (1,1), (2,2), etc., adding one pair each successive approximation because computing *factorial(n)* requires *n+1* calls.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] In the limit we get a total function from $\mathbb {N}$ to $\mathbb {N}$ defined everywhere in its domain.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Formally we model each approximation as a partial function $\mathbb {N} \rightharpoonup \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Our approximation is then repeatedly applying a function implementing "make a more defined partial factorial function", i.e. $F:(\mathbb {N} \rightharpoonup \mathbb {N} )\to (\mathbb {N} \rightharpoonup \mathbb {N} )$ , starting with the empty function (empty set).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Then we can introduce the notation *Fn* to indicate *F* applied *n* times.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] This iterative process builds a sequence of partial functions from $\mathbb {N}$ to $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Partial functions form a chain-complete partial order using ⊆ as the ordering.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Furthermore, this iterative process of better approximations of the factorial function forms an expansive (also called progressive) mapping because each $F^{i}\leq F^{i+1}$ using ⊆ as the ordering.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] So by a fixed-point theorem (specifically Bourbaki–Witt theorem), there exists a fixed point for this iterative process.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The fixed point we found is the least fixed point of *F*, because our iteration started with the smallest element in the domain (the empty set).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] To prove this we need a more complex fixed point theorem such as the Knaster–Tarski theorem.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The concept of power domains has been developed to give a denotational semantics to non-deterministic sequential programs.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Writing *P* for a power-domain constructor, the domain *P*(*D*) is the domain of non-deterministic computations of type denoted by *D*.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] There are difficulties with fairness and unboundedness in domain-theoretic models of non-determinism.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Many researchers have argued that the domain-theoretic models given above do not suffice for the more general case of concurrent computation.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For this reason various new models have been introduced.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] In the early 1980s, people began using the style of denotational semantics to give semantics for concurrent languages.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Examples include Will Clinger's work with the actor model; Glynn Winskel's work with event structures and Petri nets; and the work by Francez, Hoare, Lehmann, and de Roever (1979) on trace semantics for CSP.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] All these lines of inquiry remain under investigation (see e.g. the various denotational models for CSP).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Recently, Winskel and others have proposed the category of profunctors as a domain theory for concurrency.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] State (such as a heap) and simple imperative features can be straightforwardly modeled in the denotational semantics described above.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The key idea is to consider a command as a partial function on some domain of states.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The meaning of "`x:=3`" is then the function that takes a state to the state with `3` assigned to `x`.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The sequencing operator "`;`" is denoted by composition of functions.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Fixed-point constructions are then used to give a semantics to looping constructs, such as "`while`".
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Things become more difficult in modelling programs with local variables.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] One approach is to no longer work with domains, but instead to interpret types as functors from some category of worlds to a category of domains.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Programs are then denoted by natural continuous functions between these functors.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Many programming languages allow users to define recursive data types.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] This section deals only with functional data structures that cannot change.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Conventional imperative programming languages would typically allow the elements of such a recursive list to be changed.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The problem of *solving domain equations* is concerned with finding domains that model these kinds of datatypes.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] One approach, roughly speaking, is to consider the collection of all domains as a domain itself, and then solve the recursive definition there.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Polymorphic data types are data types that are defined with a parameter.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Lists of natural numbers, then, are of type `nat list`, while lists of strings are of `string list`.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Some researchers have developed domain theoretic models of polymorphism.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Other researchers have also modeled parametric polymorphism within constructive set theories.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] A recent research area has involved denotational semantics for object and class based programming languages.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Following the development of programming languages based on linear logic, denotational semantics have been given to languages for linear usage (see e.g. proof nets, coherence spaces) and also polynomial time complexity.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The problem of full abstraction for the sequential programming language PCF was, for a long time, a big open question in denotational semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The difficulty with PCF is that it is a very sequential language.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, there is no way to define the parallel-or function in PCF.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] It is for this reason that the approach using domains, as introduced above, yields a denotational semantics that is not fully abstract.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] This open question was mostly resolved in the 1990s with the development of game semantics and also with techniques involving logical relations.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] It is often useful to translate one programming language into another.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, a concurrent programming language might be translated into a process calculus; a high-level programming language might be translated into byte-code.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] In this context, notions from denotational semantics, such as full abstraction, help to satisfy security concerns.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] It is often considered important to connect denotational semantics with operational semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] This is especially important when the denotational semantics is rather mathematical and abstract, and the operational semantics is more concrete or closer to the computational intuitions.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] The following properties of a denotational semantics are often of interest.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] **Full abstraction**: All observationally equivalent programs have equal denotations.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For semantics in the traditional style, adequacy and full abstraction may be understood roughly as the requirement that "operational equivalence coincides with denotational equality".
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For denotational semantics in more intensional models, such as the actor model and process calculi, there are different notions of equivalence within each model, and so the concepts of adequacy and of full abstraction are a matter of debate, and harder to pin down.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Also the mathematical structure of operational semantics and denotational semantics can become very close.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] **Independence of denotational and operational semantics**: The denotational semantics should be formalized using mathematical structures that are independent of the operational semantics of a programming language; However, the underlying concepts can be closely related.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] See the section on Compositionality below.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] **Full completeness** or **definability**: Every morphism of the semantic model should be the denotation of a program.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, consider the expression "7 + 4".
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Compositionality in this case is to provide a meaning for "7 + 4" in terms of the meanings of "7", "4" and "+".
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] A basic denotational semantics in domain theory is compositional because it is given as follows.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] We start by considering program fragments, i.e. programs with free variables.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] A *typing context* assigns a type to each free variable.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For instance, in the expression (*x* + *y*) might be considered in a typing context (*x*:`nat`,*y*:`nat`).
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] We now give a denotational semantics to program fragments, using the following scheme.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] From the meaning of types we derive a meaning for typing contexts.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] As a special case, the meaning of the empty typing context, with no variables, is the domain with one element, denoted 1.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Finally, we must give a meaning to each program-fragment-in-typing-context.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Suppose that *P* is a program fragment of type σ, in typing context Γ, often written Γ⊢*P*:σ.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Then the meaning of this program-in-typing-context must be a continuous function 〚Γ⊢*P*:σ〛:〚Γ〛→〚σ〛.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] In fact, this is a general scheme for compositional denotational semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] There is nothing specific about domains and continuous functions here.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] One can work with a different category instead.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For example, in game semantics, the category of games has games as objects and strategies as morphisms: we can interpret types as games, and programs as strategies.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For a simple language without general recursion, we can make do with the category of sets and functions.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For a language with side-effects, we can work in the Kleisli category for a monad.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] For a language with state, we can work in a functor category.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Milner has advocated modelling location and interaction by working in a category with interfaces as objects and *bigraphs* as morphisms.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] It is not necessary for the semantics to determine an implementation, but it should provide criteria for showing that an implementation is correct.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Usually, however, the formal semantics of a conventional sequential programming language may itself be interpreted to provide an (inefficient) implementation of the language.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] A formal semantics need not always provide such an implementation, though, and to believe that semantics must provide an implementation leads to confusion about the formal semantics of concurrent languages.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Such confusion is painfully evident when the presence of unbounded nondeterminism in a programming language's semantics is said to imply that the programming language cannot be implemented.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Some work in denotational semantics has interpreted types as domains in the sense of domain theory, which can be seen as a branch of model theory, leading to connections with type theory and category theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/denotational-semantics] Within computer science, there are connections with abstract interpretation, program verification, and model checking.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The primary motivation for the study of domains, which was initiated by Dana Scott in the late 1960s, was the search for a denotational semantics of the lambda calculus.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In this formalism, one considers "functions" specified by certain terms in the language.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In a purely syntactic way, one can go from simple functions to functions that take other functions as their input arguments.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Using again just the syntactic transformations available in this formalism, one can obtain so-called fixed-point combinators (the best-known of which is the Y combinator); these, by definition, have the property that *f*(**Y**(*f*)) = **Y**(*f*) for all functions *f*.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] To formulate such a denotational semantics, one might first try to construct a *model* for the lambda calculus, in which a genuine (total) function is associated with each lambda term.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Such a model would formalize a link between the lambda calculus as a purely syntactic system and the lambda calculus as a notational system for manipulating concrete mathematical functions.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The combinator calculus is such a model.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] However, the elements of the combinator calculus are functions from functions to functions; in order for the elements of a model of the lambda calculus to be of arbitrary domain and range, they could not be true functions, only partial functions.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Scott got around this difficulty by formalizing a notion of "partial" or "incomplete" information to represent computations that have not yet returned a result.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] This was modeled by considering, for each domain of computation (e.g. the natural numbers), an additional element that represents an *undefined* output, i.e. the "result" of a computation that never ends.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In addition, the domain of computation is equipped with an *ordering relation*, in which the "undefined result" is the least element.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The important step to finding a model for the lambda calculus is to consider only those functions (on such a partially ordered set) that are guaranteed to have least fixed points.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The set of these functions, together with an appropriate ordering, is again a "domain" in the sense of the theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] But the restriction to a subset of all available functions has another great benefit: it is possible to obtain domains that contain their own function spaces, i.e. one gets functions that can be applied to themselves.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Beside these desirable properties, domain theory also allows for an appealing intuitive interpretation.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] As mentioned above, the domains of computation are always partially ordered.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] This ordering represents a hierarchy of information or knowledge.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The higher an element is within the order, the more specific it is and the more information it contains.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Lower elements represent incomplete knowledge or intermediate results.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Computation then is modeled by applying monotone functions repeatedly on elements of the domain in order to refine a result.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Reaching a fixed point is equivalent to finishing a calculation.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Domains provide a superior setting for these ideas since fixed points of monotone functions can be guaranteed to exist and, under additional restrictions, can be approximated from below.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In this section, the central concepts and definitions of domain theory will be introduced.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The above intuition of domains being *information orderings* will be emphasized to motivate the mathematical formalization of the theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The precise formal definitions are to be found in the dedicated articles for each concept.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] A list of general order-theoretic definitions, which include domain theoretic notions as well can be found in the order theory glossary.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The most important concepts of domain theory will nonetheless be introduced below.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] As mentioned before, domain theory deals with partially ordered sets to model a domain of computation.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The goal is to interpret the elements of such an order as *pieces of information* or *(partial) results of a computation*, where elements that are higher in the order extend the information of the elements below them in a consistent way.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] From this simple intuition it is already clear that domains often do not have a greatest element, since this would mean that there is an element that contains the information of *all* other elements—a rather uninteresting situation.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] A concept that plays an important role in the theory is that of a **directed subset** of a domain; a directed subset is a non-empty subset of the order in which any two elements have an upper bound that is an element of this subset.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In view of our intuition about domains, this means that any two pieces of information within the directed subset are *consistently* extended by some other element in the subset.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Hence we can view directed subsets as *consistent specifications*, i.e. as sets of partial results in which no two elements are contradictory.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] This interpretation can be compared with the notion of a convergent sequence in analysis, where each element is more specific than the preceding one.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Indeed, in the theory of metric spaces, sequences play a role that is in many aspects analogous to the role of directed sets in domain theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Now, as in the case of sequences, we are interested in the *limit* of a directed set.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] According to what was said above, this would be an element that is the most general piece of information that extends the information of all elements of the directed set, i.e. the unique element that contains *exactly* the information that was present in the directed set, and nothing more.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In the formalization of order theory, this is just the **least upper bound** of the directed set.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] As in the case of the limit of a sequence, the least upper bound of a directed set does not always exist.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Naturally, one has a special interest in those domains of computations in which all consistent specifications *converge*, i.e. in orders in which all directed sets have a least upper bound.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] This property defines the class of **directed-complete partial orders**, or **dcpo** for short.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Indeed, most considerations of domain theory do only consider orders that are at least directed complete.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] From the underlying idea of partially specified results as representing incomplete knowledge, one derives another desirable property: the existence of a **least element**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Such an element models that state of no information—the place where most computations start.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] It also can be regarded as the output of a computation that does not return any result at all.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Now that we have some basic formal descriptions of what a domain of computation should be, we can turn to the computations themselves.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Clearly, these have to be functions, taking inputs from some computational domain and returning outputs in some (possibly different) domain.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] However, one would also expect that the output of a function will contain more information when the information content of the input is increased.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Formally, this means that we want a function to be **monotonic**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] When dealing with **dcpos**, one might also want computations to be compatible with the formation of limits of a directed set.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Formally, this means that, for some function *f*, the image *f*(*D*) of a directed set *D* (i.e. the set of the images of each element of *D*) is again directed and has as a least upper bound the image of the least upper bound of *D*.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] One could also say that *f* *preserves directed suprema*.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Also note that, by considering directed sets of two elements, such a function also has to be monotonic.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] These properties give rise to the notion of a **Scott-continuous** function.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Since this often is not ambiguous one also may speak of *continuous functions*.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Domain theory is a purely *qualitative* approach to modeling the structure of information states.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] One can say that something contains more information, but the amount of additional information is not specified.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Yet, there are some situations in which one wants to speak about elements that are in a sense much simpler (or much more incomplete) than a given state of information.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] For example, in the natural subset-inclusion ordering on some powerset, any infinite element (i.e. set) is much more "informative" than any of its *finite* subsets.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] If one wants to model such a relationship, one may first want to consider the induced strict order < of a domain with order ≤.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] However, while this is a useful notion in the case of total orders, it does not tell us much in the case of partially ordered sets.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Considering again inclusion-orders of sets, a set is already strictly smaller than another, possibly infinite, set if it contains just one less element.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] One would, however, hardly agree that this captures the notion of being "much simpler".
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] A more elaborate approach leads to the definition of the so-called **order of approximation**, which is more suggestively also called the **way-below relation**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] since the singleton set {*y*} is directed.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] For an example, in an ordering of sets, an infinite set is way above any of its finite subsets.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Since the supremum of this chain is the set of all natural numbers **N**, this shows that no infinite set is way below **N**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] However, being way below some element is a *relative* notion and does not reveal much about an element alone.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] For example, one would like to characterize finite sets in an order-theoretic way, but even infinite sets can be way below some other set.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The special property of these **finite** elements *x* is that they are way below themselves, i.e.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] An element with this property is also called **compact**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Yet, such elements do not have to be "finite" nor "compact" in any other mathematical usage of the terms.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The notation is nonetheless motivated by certain parallels to the respective notions in set theory and topology.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The compact elements of a domain have the important special property that they cannot be obtained as a limit of a directed set in which they did not already occur.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Many other important results about the way-below relation support the claim that this definition is appropriate to capture many important aspects of a domain.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The previous thoughts raise another question: is it possible to guarantee that all elements of a domain can be obtained as a limit of much simpler elements?
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] This is quite relevant in practice, since we cannot compute infinite objects but we may still hope to approximate them arbitrarily closely.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] More generally, we would like to restrict to a certain subset of elements as being sufficient for getting all other elements as least upper bounds.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Hence, one defines a **base** of a poset *P* as being a subset *B* of *P*, such that, for each *x* in *P*, the set of elements in *B* that are way below *x* contains a directed set with supremum *x*.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The poset *P* is a **continuous poset** if it has some base.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Especially, *P* itself is a base in this situation.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In many applications, one restricts to continuous (d)cpos as a main object of study.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Finally, an even stronger restriction on a partially ordered set is given by requiring the existence of a base of *finite* elements.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] From the viewpoint of denotational semantics, algebraic posets are particularly well-behaved, since they allow for the approximation of all elements even when restricting to finite ones.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] As remarked before, not every finite element is "finite" in a classical sense and it may well be that the finite elements constitute an uncountable set.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In some cases, however, the base for a poset is countable.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] In this case, one speaks of an **ω-continuous** poset.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Accordingly, if the countable base consists entirely of finite elements, we obtain an order that is **ω-algebraic**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] A simple special case of a domain is known as an **elementary** or **flat domain**.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] This consists of a set of incomparable elements, such as the integers, along with a single "bottom" element considered smaller than all other elements.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] One can obtain a number of other interesting special classes of ordered structures that could be suitable as "domains".
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] We already mentioned continuous posets and algebraic posets.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] More special versions of both are continuous and algebraic cpos.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Adding even further completeness properties one obtains continuous lattices and algebraic lattices, which are just complete lattices with the respective properties.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] For the algebraic case, one finds broader classes of posets that are still worth studying: historically, the Scott domains were the first structures to be studied in domain theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Still wider classes of domains are constituted by SFP-domains, L-domains, and bifinite domains.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] All of these classes of orders can be cast into various categories of dcpos, using functions that are monotone, Scott-continuous, or even more specialized as morphisms.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] Finally, note that the term *domain* itself is not exact and thus is only used as an abbreviation when a formal definition has been given before or when the details are irrelevant.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] (Markowsky's theorem) A poset *D* is a dcpo if and only if it is a chain complete poset, meaning that each chain in *D* has a supremum.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] The $\sqcup$ symbol is the directed join.
[src:denotational-semantics/domain-theory] A continuity space is a generalization of metric spaces and posets that can be used to unify the notions of metric spaces and domains.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In philosophy, **meaning** is "a relationship between two sorts of things: signs and the kinds of things they intend, express, or signify".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] It is studied in the fields of semantics and philosophy of language.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Meanings can be categorised in relation to the types of things being represented.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The question of what is a proper basis for deciding how words, symbols, ideas and beliefs may properly be considered to truthfully denote meaning, whether by a single person or by an entire society, has been considered by five major types of theory of meaning and truth.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Each type is discussed below, together with its principal exponents.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Correspondence theories emphasise that true beliefs and true statements of meaning correspond to the actual state of affairs and that associated meanings must be in agreement with these beliefs and statements.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This type of theory stresses a relationship between thoughts or statements on one hand, and things or objects on the other.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] It is a traditional model tracing its origins to ancient Greek philosophers such as Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This class of theories holds that the truth or the falsity of a representation is determined in principle entirely by how it relates to "things", by whether it accurately describes those "things".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Aquinas also restated the theory as: "A judgment is said to be true when it conforms to the external reality".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Correspondence theory centres heavily around the assumption that truth and meaning are a matter of accurately copying what is known as "objective reality" and then representing it in thoughts, words and other symbols.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Many modern theorists have stated that this ideal cannot be achieved without analysing additional factors.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For example, language plays a role in that all languages have words to represent concepts that are virtually undefined in other languages.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Thus, some words add an additional parameter to the construction of an accurate truth predicate.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Among the philosophers who grappled with this problem is Alfred Tarski, whose semantic theory is summarized further below in this article.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For coherence theories in general, the assessment of meaning and truth requires a proper fit of elements within a whole system.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Very often, though, coherence is taken to imply something more than simple logical consistency; often there is a demand that the propositions in a coherent system lend mutual inferential support to each other.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] So, for example, the completeness and comprehensiveness of the underlying set of concepts is a critical factor in judging the validity and usefulness of a coherent system.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] A pervasive tenet of coherence theories is the idea that truth is primarily a property of whole systems of propositions, and can be ascribed to individual propositions only according to their coherence with the whole.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Among the assortment of perspectives commonly regarded as coherence theory, theorists differ on the question of whether coherence entails many possible true systems of thought or only a single absolute system.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Some variants of coherence theory are claimed to describe the essential and intrinsic properties of formal systems in logic and mathematics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] However, formal reasoners are content to contemplate axiomatically independent and sometimes mutually contradictory systems side by side—for example, the various alternative geometries.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Coherence theories distinguish the thought of rationalist philosophers, particularly of Spinoza, Leibniz, and G.W.F.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Hegel, along with the British philosopher F.H.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Other alternatives may be found among several proponents of logical positivism, notably Otto Neurath and Carl Hempel.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Social constructivism holds that meaning and truth are constructed by social processes, are historically and culturally specific, and are in part shaped through power struggles within a community.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Constructivism views all of our knowledge as "constructed", because it does not reflect any external "transcendent" realities (as a pure correspondence theory might hold).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Rather, perceptions of truth are viewed as contingent on convention, human perception, and social experience.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] It is believed by constructivists that representations of physical and biological reality, including race, sexuality, and gender, are socially constructed.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Giambattista Vico was among the first to claim that history and culture, along with their meaning, are human products.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Vico's epistemological orientation gathers the most diverse rays and unfolds in one axiom – *verum ipsum factum* – "truth itself is constructed".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Hegel and Marx were among the other early proponents of the premise that truth is, or can be, socially constructed.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Marx, like many critical theorists who followed, did not reject the existence of objective truth but rather distinguished between true knowledge and knowledge that has been distorted through power or ideology.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For Marx, scientific and true knowledge is "in accordance with the dialectical understanding of history" and ideological knowledge is "an epiphenomenal expression of the relation of material forces in a given economic arrangement".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Consensus theory holds that meaning and truth are whatever is agreed upon—or, in some versions, might come to be agreed upon—by some specified group.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Such a group might include all human beings, or a subset thereof consisting of more than one person.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Among the current advocates of consensus theory as a useful accounting of the concept of "truth" is the philosopher Jürgen Habermas.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Habermas maintains that truth is what would be agreed upon in an ideal speech situation.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Among the recent strong critics of consensus theory has been the philosopher Nicholas Rescher.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The three most influential forms of the *pragmatic theory of truth* and meaning were introduced around the turn of the 20th century by Charles Sanders Peirce, William James, and John Dewey.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Although there are wide differences in viewpoint among these and other proponents of pragmatic theory, they hold in common that meaning and truth are verified and confirmed by the results of putting one's concepts into practice.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] William James's version of pragmatic theory, while complex, is often summarized by his statement that "the 'true' is only the expedient in our way of thinking, just as the 'right' is only the expedient in our way of behaving".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] By this, James meant that truth is a *quality*, the value of which is confirmed by its effectiveness when applying concepts to practice (thus, "pragmatic").
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] A later variation of the pragmatic theory was William Ernest Hocking's "negative pragmatism": what works may or may not be true, but what fails cannot be true, because the truth and its meaning always works.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] James's and Dewey's ideas also ascribe meaning and truth to repeated testing, which is "self-corrective" over time.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Pragmatism and negative pragmatism are also closely aligned with the coherence theory of truth in that any testing should not be isolated but rather incorporate knowledge from all human endeavors and experience.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The universe is a whole and integrated system, and testing should acknowledge and account for its diversity.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] As physicist Richard Feynman said: "if it disagrees with experiment, it is wrong".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Some have asserted that meaning is nothing substantially more or less than the truth conditions they involve.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For such theories, an emphasis is placed upon reference to actual things in the world to account for meaning, with the caveat that reference more or less explains the greater part (or all) of meaning itself.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The logical positivists argued that the meaning of a statement arose from how it is verified.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In his paper "Über Sinn und Bedeutung" (now usually translated as "On Sense and Reference"), Gottlob Frege argued that proper names present at least two problems in explaining meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Suppose two different names refer to the same object.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *Hesperus* and *Phosphorus* were the names given to what were considered distinct celestial bodies.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] It was later shown that they were the same thing (the planet Venus).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] If the words meant the same thing, then substituting one for the other in a sentence would not result in a sentence that differs in meaning from the original.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] But in that case, "Hesperus is Phosphorus" would mean the same thing as "Hesperus is Hesperus".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This is clearly absurd, since we learn something new and unobvious by the former statement, but not by the latter.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Frege can be interpreted as arguing that it was therefore a mistake to think that the meaning of a name is the thing it refers to.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Instead, the meaning must be something else—the "sense" of the word.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Two names for the same person, then, can have different senses (or meanings): one referent might be picked out by more than one sense.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This sort of theory is called a mediated reference theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Frege argued that, ultimately, the same bifurcation of meaning must apply to most or all linguistic categories, such as to quantificational expressions like "All boats float".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Logical analysis was further advanced by Bertrand Russell and Alfred North Whitehead in their groundbreaking *Principia Mathematica*, which attempted to produce a formal language with which the truth of all mathematical statements could be demonstrated from first principles.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Russell differed from Frege greatly on many points, however.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He rejected Frege's sense-reference distinction.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He hoped, ultimately, to extend the proofs of the *Principia* to all possible true statements, a scheme he called logical atomism.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For a while it appeared that his pupil Wittgenstein had succeeded in this plan with his *Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus*.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Russell's work, and that of his colleague G.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Moore, developed in response to what they perceived as the nonsense dominating British philosophy departments at the turn of the 20th century, which was a kind of British Idealism most of which was derived (albeit very distantly) from the work of Hegel.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In response Moore developed an approach ("Common Sense Philosophy") which sought to examine philosophical difficulties by a close analysis of the language used in order to determine its meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In this way Moore sought to expunge philosophical absurdities such as "time is unreal".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Moore's work would have significant, if oblique, influence (largely mediated by Wittgenstein) on Ordinary language philosophy.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The Vienna Circle, a famous group of logical positivists from the early 20th century (closely allied with Russell and Frege), adopted the verificationist theory of meaning, a type of **truth theory of meaning**.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The verificationist theory of meaning (in at least one of its forms) states that to say that an expression is meaningful is to say that there are some conditions of experience that could exist to show that the expression is true.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] As noted, Frege and Russell were two proponents of this way of thinking.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] A semantic theory of truth was produced by Alfred Tarski for formal semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] According to Tarski's account, meaning consists of a recursive set of rules that end up yielding an infinite set of sentences, "'p' is true if and only if p", covering the whole language.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] His innovation produced the notion of propositional functions discussed on the section on universals (which he called "sentential functions"), and a model-theoretic approach to semantics (as opposed to a proof-theoretic one).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Finally, some links were forged to the correspondence theory of truth (Tarski, 1944).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Perhaps the most influential current approach in the contemporary theory of meaning is that sketched by Donald Davidson in his introduction to the collection of essays *Truth and Meaning* in 1967.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The result is a theory of meaning that rather resembles, by no accident, Tarski's account.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Davidson's account, though brief, constitutes the first systematic presentation of truth-conditional semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He proposed simply translating natural languages into first-order predicate calculus in order to reduce meaning to a function of truth.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Saul Kripke examined the relation between sense and reference in dealing with possible and actual situations.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He showed that one consequence of his interpretation of certain systems of modal logic was that the reference of a proper name is *necessarily* linked to its referent, but that the sense is not.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] So for instance "Hesperus" necessarily refers to Hesperus, even in those imaginary cases and worlds in which perhaps Hesperus is not the evening star.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] That is, Hesperus is necessarily Hesperus, but only contingently the morning star.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This results in the curious situation that part of the meaning of a name — that it refers to some particular thing — is a necessary fact about that name, but another part — that it is used in some particular way or situation — is not.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Kripke also drew the distinction between speaker's meaning and semantic meaning, elaborating on the work of ordinary language philosophers Paul Grice and Keith Donnellan.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The speaker's meaning is what the speaker intends to refer to by saying something; the semantic meaning is what the words uttered by the speaker mean according to the language.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In some cases, people do not say what they mean; in other cases, they say something that is in error.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In both these cases, the speaker's meaning and the semantic meaning seem to be different.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Sometimes words do not actually express what the speaker wants them to express; so words will mean one thing, and what people intend to convey by them might mean another.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The meaning of the expression, in such cases, is ambiguous.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Quine attacked both verificationism and the very notion of meaning in his famous essay, "Two Dogmas of Empiricism".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In it, he suggested that meaning was nothing more than a vague and dispensable notion.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Instead, he asserted, what was more interesting to study was the synonymy between signs.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He also pointed out that verificationism was tied to the distinction between analytic and synthetic statements, and asserted that such a divide was defended ambiguously.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He also suggested that the unit of analysis for any potential investigation into the world (and, perhaps, meaning) would be the entire body of statements taken as a collective, not just individual statements on their own.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Other criticisms can be raised on the basis of the limitations that truth-conditional theorists themselves admit to.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Tarski, for instance, recognized that truth-conditional theories of meaning only make sense of statements, but fail to explain the meanings of the lexical parts that make up statements.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Rather, the meaning of the parts of statements is presupposed by an understanding of the truth-conditions of a whole statement, and explained in terms of what he called "satisfaction conditions".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Still another objection (noted by Frege and others) was that some kinds of statements do not seem to have any truth-conditions at all.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For instance, "Hello!" has no truth-conditions, because it does not even attempt to tell the listener anything about the state of affairs in the world.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In other words, different propositions have different grammatical moods.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Deflationist accounts of truth, sometimes called 'irrealist' accounts, are the staunchest source of criticism of truth-conditional theories of meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] According to them, "truth" is a word with no serious meaning or function in discourse.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For instance, for the deflationist, the sentences "It's true that Tiny Tim is trouble" and "Tiny Tim is trouble" are equivalent.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In consequence, for the deflationist, any appeal to truth as an account of meaning has little explanatory power.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The sort of truth theories presented here can also be attacked for their formalism both in practice and principle.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The principle of formalism is challenged by the informalists, who suggest that language is largely a construction of the speaker, and so, not compatible with formalization.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Finally, over the past century, forms of logic have been developed that are not dependent exclusively on the notions of truth and falsity.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Some of these types of logic have been called modal logics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] They explain how certain logical connectives such as "if-then" work in terms of necessity and possibility.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Indeed, modal logic was the basis of one of the most popular and rigorous formulations in modern semantics called the Montague grammar.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The successes of such systems naturally give rise to the argument that these systems have captured the natural meaning of connectives like if-then far better than an ordinary, truth-functional logic ever could.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Throughout the 20th century, English philosophy focused closely on analysis of language.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This style of analytic philosophy became very influential and led to the development of a wide range of philosophical tools.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein was originally an ideal language philosopher, following the influence of Russell and Frege.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In his *Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus* he had supported the idea of an ideal language built up from atomic statements using logical connectives (see picture theory of meaning and logical atomism).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] However, as he matured, he came to appreciate more and more the phenomenon of natural language.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *Philosophical Investigations*, published after his death, signalled a sharp departure from his earlier work with its focus upon ordinary language use (see use theory of meaning and ordinary language philosophy).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] His approach is often summarised by the aphorism "the meaning of a word is its use in a language".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] However, following in Frege's footsteps, in the *Tractatus*, Wittgenstein declares: "...
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] His work would come to inspire future generations and spur forward a whole new discipline, which explained meaning in a new way.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Meaning in a natural language was seen as primarily a question of how the speaker uses words within the language to express intention.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This close examination of natural language proved to be a powerful philosophical technique.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Practitioners who were influenced by Wittgenstein's approach have included an entire tradition of thinkers, featuring P.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] At around the same time Ludwig Wittgenstein was re-thinking his approach to language, reflections on the complexity of language led to a more expansive approach to meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Following the lead of George Edward Moore, J.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Austin examined the use of words in great detail.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He argued against fixating on the meaning of words.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He showed that dictionary definitions are of limited philosophical use, since there is no simple "appendage" to a word that can be called its meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Instead, he showed how to focus on the way in which words are used in order to do things.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He analysed the structure of utterances into three distinct parts: locutions, illocutions and perlocutions.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] His pupil John Searle developed the idea under the label "speech acts".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Their work greatly influenced pragmatics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Past philosophers had understood reference to be tied to words themselves.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] However, Peter Strawson disagreed in his seminal essay, "On Referring", where he argued that there is nothing true about statements on their own; rather, only the uses of statements could be considered to be true or false.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Indeed, one of the hallmarks of the ordinary use perspective is its insistence upon the distinctions between meaning and use.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *"Meanings"*, for ordinary language philosophers, are the *instructions* for usage of words — the common and conventional definitions of words.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *Usage*, on the other hand, is the actual meanings that individual speakers have — the things that an individual speaker in a particular context wants to refer to.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The word "dog" is an example of a meaning, but pointing at a nearby dog and shouting "This dog smells foul!" is an example of usage.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] From this distinction between usage and meaning arose the divide between the fields of pragmatics and semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Yet another distinction is of some utility in discussing language: "mentioning".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *Mention* is when an expression refers to itself as a linguistic item, usually surrounded by quotation marks.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For instance, in the expression "'Opopanax' is hard to spell", what is referred to is the word itself ("opopanax") and not what it means (an obscure gum resin).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Frege had referred to instances of mentioning as "opaque contexts".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In his essay, "Reference and Definite Descriptions", Keith Donnellan sought to improve upon Strawson's distinction.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He pointed out that there are two uses of definite descriptions: *attributive* and *referential*.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Attributive uses provide a description of whoever is being referred to, while referential uses point out the actual referent.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Attributive uses are like mediated references, while referential uses are more directly referential.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The philosopher Paul Grice, working within the ordinary language tradition, understood "meaning" — in his 1957 article — to have two kinds: *natural* and *non-natural*.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *Natural meaning* had to do with cause and effect, for example with the expression "these spots mean measles".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] *Non-natural* meaning, on the other hand, had to do with the intentions of the speaker in communicating something to the listener.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In his essay, *Logic and Conversation*, Grice went on to explain and defend an explanation of how conversations work.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] His guiding maxim was called the *cooperative principle*, which claimed that the speaker and the listener will have mutual expectations of the kind of information that will be shared.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The principle is broken down into four maxims: *Quality* (which demands truthfulness and honesty), *Quantity* (demand for just enough information as is required), *Relation* (relevance of things brought up), and *Manner* (lucidity).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This principle, if and when followed, lets the speaker and listener figure out the meaning of certain implications by way of inference.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The works of Grice led to an avalanche of research and interest in the field, both supportive and critical.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] One spinoff was called Relevance theory, developed by Dan Sperber and Deirdre Wilson during the mid-1980s, whose goal was to make the notion of *relevance* more clear.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Similarly, in his work, "Universal pragmatics", Jürgen Habermas began a program that sought to improve upon the work of the ordinary language tradition.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In it, he laid out the goal of a valid conversation as a pursuit of mutual understanding.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Although he has focused on the structure and functioning of human syntax, in many works Noam Chomsky has discussed many philosophical problems too, including the problem of meaning and reference in human language.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Chomsky has formulated a strong criticism against both the externalist notion of reference (reference consists in a direct or causal relation among words and objects) and the internalist one (reference is a mind-mediated relation holding among words and reality).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] As Chomsky himself has pointed out, this conception of meaning is very close to that adopted by John Austin, Peter Strawson and the late Wittgenstein.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Michael Dummett argued against the kind of truth-conditional semantics presented by Davidson.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Instead, he argued that basing semantics on *assertion conditions* avoids a number of difficulties with truth-conditional semantics, such as the transcendental nature of certain kinds of truth condition.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] A semantics based upon assertion conditions is called a verificationist semantics: cf. the verificationism of the Vienna Circle.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] This work is closely related, though not identical, to one-factor theories of conceptual role semantics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Sometimes between the 1950-1990s, cognitive scientist Jerry Fodor said that use theories of meaning (of the Wittgensteinian kind) seem to assume that language is solely a public phenomenon, that there is no such thing as a "private language".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Fodor thinks it is necessary to create or describe the *language of thought*, which would seemingly require the existence of a "private language".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In the 1960s, David Kellogg Lewis described meaning as use, a feature of a social convention and conventions as regularities of a specific sort.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Lewis' work was an application of game theory in philosophical topics.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Conventions, he argued, are a species of coordination equilibria.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The **idea theory of meaning** (also **ideational theory of meaning**), most commonly associated with the British empiricist John Locke, claims that meanings are mental representations provoked by signs.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The term "ideas" is used to refer to either mental representations, or to mental activity in general.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Those who seek an explanation for meaning in the former sort of account endorse a stronger sort of idea theory of mind than the latter.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Each idea is understood to be necessarily *about* something external and/or internal, real or imaginary.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For example, in contrast to the abstract meaning of the universal "dog", the referent "this dog" may mean a particular real life chihuahua.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In both cases, the word is about something, but in the former it is about the class of dogs as generally understood, while in the latter it is about a very real and particular dog in the real world.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] John Locke considered all ideas to be both imaginable objects of sensation and the very *un*imaginable objects of reflection.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He said in his *Essay Concerning Human Understanding* that words are used both as signs for ideas and also to signify a lack of certain ideas.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] David Hume held that thoughts were kinds of imaginable entities: his *Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding*, section 2.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] He argued that any words that could not call upon any past experience were without meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] In contrast to Locke and Hume, George Berkeley and Ludwig Wittgenstein held that ideas alone are unable to account for the different variations within a general meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For example, any hypothetical image of the meaning of "dog" has to include such varied images as a chihuahua, a pug, and a black Labrador; and this seems impossible to imagine, since all of those particular breeds look very different from one another.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Another way to see this point is to question why it is that, if we have an image of a specific type of dog (say of a chihuahua), it should be entitled to represent the entire concept.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Another criticism is that some meaningful words, known as non-lexical items, do not have any meaningfully associated image.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For example, the word "the" has a meaning, but one would be hard-pressed to find a mental representation that fits it.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Still another objection lies in the observation that certain linguistic items name something in the real world, and are meaningful, yet which we have no mental representations to deal with.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For instance, it is not known what Newton's father looked like, yet the phrase *"Newton's father"* still has meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Another problem is that of composition—that it is difficult to explain how words and phrases combine into sentences if only ideas are involved in meaning.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Eleanor Rosch and George Lakoff have advanced a theory of "prototypes" which suggests that many lexical categories, at least on the face of things, have "radial structures".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] That is to say, there are some ideal member(s) in the category that seem to represent the category better than other members.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] For example, the category of "birds" may feature the *robin* as the prototype, or the ideal kind of bird.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] With experience, subjects might come to evaluate membership in the category of "bird" by comparing candidate members to the prototype and evaluating for similarities.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] So, for example, a penguin or an ostrich would sit at the fringe of the meaning of "bird", because a penguin is unlike a robin.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Intimately related to these researches is the notion of a *psychologically basic level*, which is both the first level named and understood by children, and "the highest level at which a single mental image can reflect the entire category" (Lakoff 1987:46).
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] The "basic level" of cognition is understood by Lakoff as crucially drawing upon "image-schemas" along with various other cognitive processes.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Philosophers Ned Block, Gilbert Harman and Hartry Field, and cognitive scientists G.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Johnson-Laird say that the meaning of a term can be found by investigating its role in relation to other concepts and mental states.
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] They endorse a "conceptual role semantics".
[src:denotational-semantics/meaning-philosophy] Those proponents of this view who understand meanings to be exhausted by the content of mental states can be said to endorse "one-factor" accounts of conceptual role semantics and thus to fit within the tradition of idea theories.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] In the mathematical fields of order and domain theory, a **Scott domain** is an algebraic, bounded-complete and directed-complete partial order (dcpo).
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Scott, who was the first to study these structures at the advent of domain theory.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Scott domains are very closely related to algebraic lattices, being different only in possibly lacking a greatest element.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] They are also closely related to Scott information systems, which constitute a "syntactic" representation of Scott domains.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] While the term "Scott domain" is widely used with the above definition, the term "domain" does not have such a generally accepted meaning and different authors will use different definitions; Scott himself used "domain" for the structures now called "Scott domains".
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Additionally, Scott domains appear with other names like "algebraic semilattice" in some publications.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Originally, Dana Scott demanded a complete lattice, and the Russian mathematician Yuri Yershov constructed the isomorphic structure of a directed-complete partial order (dcpo).
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] But this was not recognized until after scientific communications improved after the fall of the Iron Curtain.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] In honour of their work, a number of mathematical papers now dub this fundamental construction a "Scott–Ershov" domain.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Since the empty set certainly has some upper bound, we can conclude the existence of a least element $\bot$ (the supremum of the empty set) from bounded completeness.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] The property of being bounded-complete is equivalent to the existence of infima of all *non-empty* subsets of D.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] It is well known that the existence of *all* infima implies the existence of all suprema and thus makes a partially ordered set into a complete lattice.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] 2. the resulting poset will be an algebraic lattice (i.e. a complete lattice that is algebraic).
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Consequently, Scott domains are in a sense "almost" algebraic lattices.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] However, removing the top element from a complete lattice does not always produce a Scott domain.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] (Consider the complete lattice ${\mathcal {P}}(\mathbb {N} )$ .
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Scott domains become topological spaces by introducing the Scott topology.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Scott domains are intended to represent *partial algebraic data*, ordered by information content.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] An element $x\in D$ is a piece of data that might not be fully defined.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] The statement $x\leq y$ means " y contains all the information that x does".
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] The bottom element is the element containing no information at all.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Compact elements are the elements representing a finite amount of information.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] With this interpretation we can see that the supremum $\bigvee X$ of a subset $X\subseteq D$ is the element that contains all the information that *any* element of X contains, but *no more*.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] Obviously such a supremum only exists (i.e., makes sense) provided X does not contain inconsistent information; hence the domain is directed and bounded complete, but not *all* suprema necessarily exist.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] On the other hand, the infimum $\bigwedge X$ is the element that contains all the information that is shared by *all* elements of X , and *no less*.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] If X contains no consistent information, then its elements have no information in common and so its infimum is $\bot$ .
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] In this way all non-empty infima exist, but not all infima are necessarily interesting.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] This definition in terms of partial data allows an algebra to be defined as the limit of a sequence of increasingly more defined partial algebras—in other words a fixed point of an operator that adds progressively more information to the algebra.
[src:denotational-semantics/scott-domain] For more information, see Domain theory.
